%N A330491 Non-palindromic balanced primes in base 3.
%C A330491 A number is called "balanced" here if the sum of digits weighted by their arithmetic distance from the "center" of the number is zero. Palindromic primes (A029971) are "trivially" balanced, so they are excluded here.
%C A330491 These are the primes in A256083, respectively the intersection of A000040 and A256083.
%H A330491 Thorben Böger, <a href="/A330491/b330491.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..19999</a>
%e A330491 a(7) = 1471 as 1471 is prime and 2000111 in base 3, which is balanced: 3*2 = 1*1 + 2*1 + 3*1.
%t A330491 A330491Q[p_] := Plus @@ (#*(Range[-#, #] & [(Length[#]-1)/2])) == 0 && !PalindromeQ[#] & [IntegerDigits[p, 3]];
%t A330491 Select[Prime[Range[1500]], A330491Q] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Jan 20 2026 *)
%o A330491 (Python)
%o A330491 from sympy import primerange
%o A330491 from sympy.ntheory.digits import digits
%o A330491 def isbalanced(converted):
%o A330491     return sum([(place*2 - (len(converted) - 1))*digit for place, digit in enumerate(converted)]) == 0
%o A330491 balanced_primes_list = [prime for prime in primerange(20000) if(digits(prime, 3)[1:] != digits(prime, 3)[1:][::-1] and isbalanced(digits(prime, 3)[1:]))] # edited by _Jason Yuen_, Jan 18 2026
